# Changes Made to Create path.tracking v2.0.0

---

Bug Fixes

1. Vehicle.accelerate() used wrong prim reference
- What: accelerate() called self._vehicle() (an internal method that does a stage path
lookup) while every other control method (brake, steer_left, steer_right) used self._prim
directly.
- Why fixed: Unnecessary stage lookup on every physics tick, and inconsistency that would
break if the prim path ever changed between the constructor and the call.
1. PurePursuitScenario.teardown() crashed on None
- What: teardown() called self._dest.teardown(), but self._dest was assigned None in**init** and never given an object.
- Why fixed: This would raise AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'teardown' every time the extension shut down.
1. load_sample_vehicle() silently discarded the vehicle path
- What: The method computed root_vehicle_path, then immediately overwrote it with a
get_stage_next_free_path call for root_shared_path, passing the wrong path to the wizard
command.
- Why fixed: The returned path was always the shared-data path, so any code that used the
return value to set up the preset attachment was pointing at the wrong prim.
1. Scenario.teardown() called non-existent super().abort()
- What: PurePursuitScenario.teardown() called super().abort(), but the Scenario base class
only defines on_start, on_step, and on_end — no abort().
- Why fixed: Would raise AttributeError on shutdown. The entire teardown() method was dead, unreachable code anyway (it was never called by ScenarioManager), so it was removed.

---

Architectural Changes

1. Replaced omni.debugdraw with omni.ui.scene
- What: Deleted debug_draw.py and wrote scene_draw.py from scratch. The new
SceneDebugRenderer uses a sc.Manipulator subclass (_DebugManipulator) that rebuilds its
sc.Line primitives on each physics tick via invalidate().
- Why: omni.debugdraw was already flagged inside the original code's own comments as "not
future-proof" and "may change or not be kept." omni.ui.scene is the current
NVIDIA-recommended approach for viewport overlays, and it doesn't carry an unstable
dependency.
1. Renamed module from ext.path.tracking to omni.path.tracking
- What: Moved all Python files to omni/path/tracking/ and updated extension.toml
accordingly.
- Why: NVIDIA's extension naming convention requires the publisher prefix (omni.*,
company.*). ext. is not a valid namespace and causes discovery issues in the Extension
Manager.
1. Replaced asyncio.run_coroutine_threadsafe with asyncio.ensure_future
- What: All async button handlers now use asyncio.ensure_future(_coro()) instead of
asyncio.run_coroutine_threadsafe(_coro(), loop=run_loop).
- Why: Kit runs a single asyncio event loop on the main thread. run_coroutine_threadsafe is intended for scheduling from a different thread; using it from the main thread is
incorrect and can cause subtle ordering bugs. ensure_future schedules on the
already-running loop directly.

---

Dependency Changes

1. Removed omni.debugdraw dependency
- Why: No longer used. Keeping it would cause load failures in Kit versions where it has
been removed.
1. Added omni.kit.viewport.utility dependency
- Why: Required by scene_draw.py to obtain the active viewport window so the sc.SceneView
overlay can be attached to it.
1. Removed omni.physx.ui and omni.physx.commands from required deps
- Why: Neither was directly imported by any extension code. omni.physx.commands calls are
routed through omni.kit.commands.execute, which resolves them at runtime without a hard
dependency.

---

Code Quality

1. Renamed internal parameters to fix typos
- What: max_lookahed_distance / min_lookahed_distance (misspelled in the original
constructor) → max_lookahead_distance / min_lookahead_distance.
- Why: Typos in public API parameters are confusing and make autocomplete unreliable.
1. Unified _stop_and_cleanup_managers() helper in [model.py](http://model.py/)
- What: The two nearly-identical blocks that stopped and cleared scenario managers were
consolidated into one private method.
- Why: The original had the same three-line sequence copy-pasted in teardown(),
clear_attachments(), and _cleanup_scenario_managers(), which risked the copies drifting out of sync.
1. Added carb.log_warn / carb.log_error in place of silent failures
- What: attach_vehicle_to_curve(), load_sample_vehicle(), and
SceneDebugRenderer._setup_viewport_overlay() now log actionable warnings/errors instead of
silently doing nothing.
- Why: Silent failures make debugging impossible — the user sees no vehicle movement and
has no idea why.
1. Graceful viewport overlay degradation
- What: SceneDebugRenderer._setup_viewport_overlay() wraps the entire setup in try/except
and logs a warning if it fails.
- Why: In headless test environments there is no active viewport. The original
omni.debugdraw approach would also fail silently in that case; now it fails explicitly but
without crashing.
